quote:
Thus says the Lord. Here, after he had promised liberation from evils, he begins to promise salvation in the conferring of goods. And this is divided into three parts:

in the first part, the preparation of salvation is set out;

in the second, the promise of salvation: arise, be enlightened (ch. 60);

in the third, the great separation in the conferring of salvation: who is this? (ch. 63).

The first of these is divided into two:

in the first, the preparation on the part of the recipient of salvation is set out;

in the second, on the part of the savior himself: behold the hand of the Lord is not shortened (ch. 59).

The first of these is divided into two:

in the first, he gives beneficial counsel of preparation;

in the second, he excludes vain remedy: cry, cease not (ch. 58).

The first of these is divided into two:

in the first, he sets out the diversity of the recipients of this counsel, as to constitution of rewards;

in the second, their diversity as to escape from dangers: the just perishes (ch. 57).

The first of these is divided into three:

in the first, he sets out the counsel;

in the second, the fruit of the counsel in the recipients: blessed is the man that doth this (Isa 56:2);

in the third, the lack of salvation in those who hold it in contempt: all you beasts (Isa 56:9).

Concerning the first, he does two things.

First, he considers the due preparation: keep judgment, you superiors, to whom it belongs to judge; do justice, you subjects, that is, do every virtue, in as far as it is conformed to others by the precepts of the law: I will show you, O man, what is good, and what the Lord requires of you: Verily to do judgment, and to love mercy, and to walk solicitous with your God (Mic 6:8).

Second, he promises the nearness of salvation: for my salvation is near, for you shall be saved by me after your captivity, and my justice, as to your enemies, from whom I will vindicate you, above: I have brought my justice near, it shall not be afar off (Isa 46:12).

And as to foreigners: and the children of the stranger, that is, I will give them the privileges in which the Jews glory, to worship him, as to special worship, and to love his name, like children, to be his servants, and to glory in his dominion, above: they shall worship the Lord (Isa 19:21). And these things were indeed fulfilled in the return of the people from captivity, but more fully in the conversion of the gentiles to the faith of Christ, as to the Gloss explains.

Note also that the name of God is to be loved (see 56:6),

first, because it is great to be feared: my name is great among the Gentiles, says the Lord (Mal 1:11);

second, because it is holy to be venerated: he that is mighty has done great things to me: and holy is his name (Luke 1:49);

third, because it is sweet to be meditated upon, above: your name, and your remembrance are the desire of the soul (Isa 26:8);

fourth, because it is abundant to show mercy: your name is as oil poured out (Song 1:2);

fifth, because it is effective to be called upon: whatsoever you shall ask of the Father in my name, he will give it you (John 15:16);

sixth, because it is powerful to save: for there is no other name under heaven, whereby we must be saved (Acts 4:12);

seventh, because it is hidden for knowing: what is his name? (Prov 30:4).

Within my walls, a place, that is, a dwelling within the walls of my city; and a name better, because they will be called my servants and holy ones, and sons, that is, as if they had begotten many sons: the eunuch, that has not wrought iniquity (Wis 3:14).

Note on the words, I will give to them . . . a name better, that the saints have a name

first, from predestination, above: the Lord has called me from the womb, from the bowels of my mother he has been mindful of my name (Isa 49:1);

second, from divine obtaining, behold what manner of charity the Father has bestowed upon us, that we should be called and should be the sons of God (1 John 3:1);

third, from the infusion of grace: you have a name and hold fast my name (Rev 2:13);

fourth, from the renewal of their minds: I will give him a white counter: and in the counter, a new name written (Rev 2:17).
